SIMPLE: soft
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Soft
<hw>Soft</hw> <pr>(s⟦ocr⟧ft; 115)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Softer</adjf>
<pr>(s⟦ocr⟧ft"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Softest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>softe</ets>, AS.
<ets>s⟦omac⟧fte</ets>, properly adv. of <ets>s⟦emac⟧fte</ets>, adj.;
akin to OS. <ets>s⟦amac⟧fto</ets>, adv., D. <ets>zacht</ets>, OHG.
<ets>samfto</ets>, adv., <ets>semfti</ets>, adj., G. <ets>sanft</ets>,
LG. <ets>sacht</ets>; of uncertain origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Easily yielding to pressure; easily impressed, molded, or cut; not
firm in resisting; impressible; yielding; also, malleable; -- opposed to
<ant>hard</ant>; <as>as, a <ex>soft</ex> bed; a <ex>soft</ex> peach;
<ex>soft</ex> earth; <ex>soft</ex> wood or metal.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not rough, rugged, or harsh to the touch; smooth;
delicate; fine; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex> silk; a <ex>soft</ex>
skin.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that wear <qex>soft</qex> clothing are in king's houses.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xi. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, agreeable to feel, taste, or inhale; not
irritating to the tissues; <as>as, a <ex>soft</ex> liniment;
<ex>soft</ex> wines</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>soft</xex>, delicious
air.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not harsh or offensive to the sight; not glaring;
pleasing to the eye; not exciting by intensity of color or violent
contrast; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex> hues or tints</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun, shining upon the upper part of the clouds . . . made the
<qex>softest</qex> lights imaginable.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not harsh or rough in sound; gentle and pleasing to
the ear; flowing; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex> whispers of
music</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her voice was ever <qex>soft</qex>,⟦br⟧
Gentle, and low, -- an excellent thing in woman.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Soft</qex> were my numbers; who could take offense?</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Easily yielding; susceptible to influence; flexible;
gentle; kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would to God my heart were flint, like Edward's;⟦br⟧
Or Edward's <qex>soft</qex> and pitiful, like mine.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The meek or <qex>soft</qex> shall inherit the earth.</q>
<rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Expressing gentleness, tenderness, or the like;
mild; conciliatory; courteous; kind; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex>
eyes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>soft</qex> answer turneth away wrath.</q> <rj><qau>Prov.
xv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A face with gladness overspread,⟦br⟧
<qex>Soft</qex> smiles, by human kindness bred.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Effeminate; not courageous or manly, weak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A longing after sensual pleasures is a dissolution of the spirit
of a man, and makes it loose, <qex>soft</qex>, and wandering.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Gentle in action or motion; easy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On her <qex>soft</qex> axle, white she paces even,⟦br⟧
And bears thee soft with the smooth air along.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Weak in character; impressible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The deceiver soon found this <qex>soft</qex> place of Adam's.</q>
<rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Somewhat weak in intellect.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He made <qex>soft</qex> fellows stark noddies, and such as were
foolish quite mad.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Quiet; undisturbed; paceful; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex>
slumbers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>Having, or consisting of, a gentle curve or curves;
not angular or abrupt; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex> outlines</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>Not tinged with mineral salts; adapted to decompose
soap; <as>as, <ex>soft</ex> water is the best for
washing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Applied to a
palatal, a sibilant, or a dental consonant (as <xex>g</xex> in
<xex>gem</xex>, <xex>c</xex> in <xex>cent</xex>, etc.) as distinguished
from a guttural mute (as <xex>g</xex> in <xex>go</xex>, <xex>c</xex> in
<xex>cone</xex>, etc.); -- opposed to <ant>hard</ant>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Belonging to the class of sonant elements as
distinguished from the surd, and considered as involving less force in
utterance; <as>as, <ex>b</ex>, <ex>d</ex>, <ex>g</ex>, <ex>z</ex>,
<ex>v</ex>, etc.</as>, in contrast with <xex>p</xex>, <xex>t</xex>,
<xex>k</xex>, <xex>s</xex>, <xex>f</xex>, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Soft clam</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the common or
long clam (<spn>Mya arenaria</spn>). See <er>Mya</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Soft coal</b></col>, <cd>bituminous coal, as distinguished from
<xex>anthracite</xex>, or <xex>hard, coal</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Soft
crab</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any crab which has recently shed
its shell.</cd> -- <col><b>Soft dorsal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>the posterior part of the dorsal fin of fishes when supported by
soft rays.</cd> -- <col><b>Soft grass</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<cd>See <er>Velvet grass</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Soft money</b></col>,
<cd>paper money, as distinguished from <xex>coin</xex>, or <xex>hard
money</xex>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Soft
mute</b></col>. <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <cd>See <er>Media</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Soft palate</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under
<er>Palate</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Soft ray</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>a fin ray which is articulated and usually branched.</cd> --
<col><b>Soft soap</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Soap</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Soft-tack</b></col>, <cd>leavened bread, as distinguished from
<contr>hard-tack</contr>, or <contr>ship bread</contr>.</cd> --
<col><b>Soft tortoise</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any river
tortoise of the genus Trionyx. See <er>Trionyx</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soft</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Soft
<hw>Soft</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A soft or foolish person;
an idiot.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soft</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Soft
<hw>Soft</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Softly; without roughness or
harshness; gently; quietly.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A knight <qex>soft</qex> riding toward them.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soft</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Soft
<hw>Soft</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Be quiet; hold; stop; not so
fast.</def><-- archaic or obs. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Soft</qex>, you; a word or two before you go.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Softa</ent>⟦br⟧
